<timing_attacks_guide>
<title>TIMING ATTACKS AND SIDE-CHANNEL ANALYSIS</title>

<critical>Timing attacks exploit measurable differences in processing time to infer sensitive information. These side-channel vulnerabilities can reveal password validity, user enumeration, cryptographic secrets, and hidden functionality. Modern high-resolution timing APIs and network conditions make these attacks increasingly practical against web applications.</critical>

<scope>
- User enumeration via timing differences
- Password/credential validation timing
- Cryptographic key extraction
- Race condition exploitation
- Time-based blind injection
- Resource-based timing inference
- TOCTOU (Time-of-check to time-of-use) vulnerabilities
</scope>

<methodology>
1. Identify operations with potential timing variance (auth, crypto, database lookups).
2. Establish baseline timing with known-valid vs known-invalid inputs.
3. Collect sufficient samples to achieve statistical significance.
4. Apply statistical analysis to detect timing differences.
5. Correlate timing patterns with sensitive information leakage.
</methodology>

