<validation>
1. Demonstrate statistically significant timing difference (p < 0.05) between conditions.
2. Show extracted information (valid users, password characters) via timing.
3. Prove race condition exploitation with successful double-spend or privilege escalation.
4. Document sample sizes, statistical methods, and confidence intervals.
5. Provide reproducible measurement scripts and analysis.
</validation>

<false_positives>
- Timing differences within network jitter range
- Insufficient sample size for statistical significance
- Application uses constant-time comparisons
- Caching creating artificial timing patterns
- Rate limiting affecting measurement accuracy
</false_positives>

<impact>
- User/account enumeration
- Credential/password extraction
- Cryptographic key material leakage
- Race condition exploitation (double-spending, privilege escalation)
- Hidden functionality discovery
- Session/token prediction
- Authorization bypass via TOCTOU
</impact>

<pro_tips>
1. Always collect multiple samples - single requests are noise.
2. Use statistical tests appropriate for your data distribution.
3. Warm up connections before measuring to reduce variance.
4. Test from same geographic region as target for reduced jitter.
5. Server-Timing header can reveal internal timing if exposed.
6. Race conditions require parallel request capability - use appropriate tools.
7. Constant-time comparison libraries prevent password timing attacks.
8. Cache timing can reveal access patterns and user behavior.
9. For blind SQL injection, use conditional timing with known-true/false.
10. HTTP/2 multiplexing enables more precise timing attacks.
</pro_tips>

<remember>Timing attacks transform microsecond differences into information leakage. Statistical rigor is essential - collect sufficient samples and apply appropriate statistical tests. The most impactful timing attacks target authentication, cryptographic operations, and race-condition-prone state changes.</remember>
</timing_attacks_guide>
